Independent schools in Scotland are constantly celebrating their academic achievements  In 2018, they boasted further excellent test scores, supported by individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other social endeavours.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools with over 30 000 pupils across Scotland strive to provide the best possible level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career paths and their role as global citizens.
As the education sector has the capacity to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to another person in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last examination this year show that languages are at the top of the league rankings, with the highest achievement rates occurring in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language scored higher than A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher A in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also achieved A's.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, language learning as an elective subject is taught in the same way as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in independent and non-selective school curricula.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that lack of language skills was the reason for the difficulties of jobseekers in filling vacancies in 17 per cent of jobseekers.
Language skills are therefore increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for their career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills.
A lifelong skill such as learning a second language will provide a huge advantage in the future  regardless of the career path chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language where the percentage of people using it was two-digit, or 15%.
That's why investing in foreign language learning is so important for today's children.
Knowledge of several languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child's interests, there will always be a wide range of languages to choose from in independent schools, taught by specialised teaching staff.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to creating a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed  no matter what the future holds.
Today, there is no denying that in the international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of a country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide range of choice, diversity and level.
It's just the way it's supposed to be.
John Edward, chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
