North Korea calls for unilateral disarmament without trust.
North Korea's foreign minister said in a speech at the United Nations on Saturday that the failure to lift sanctions only deepened North Korea's distrust of the United States and there was no way the country would unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test sites and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"We don't see any concrete response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security, and under these circumstances, there is no question of unilateral disarmament of North Korea".
While Ri echoed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's reluctance to adopt a "gradual" approach to denuclearization, whereby North Korea would be rewarded for taking steps gradually, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as has happened in the past.
Ri was referring to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the sitting US president and the North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim Jong-un pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump promised guarantees of North Korea's security.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (1950-53), but the United States delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States is insisting on denuclearization first and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the signing of the 'end of war declaration,'" Ri said.
The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a figment of the human race that is behaving in a way that ignores us.
The problem is that the lack of sanctions increases our distrust.
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which the US leader had spoken about earlier this week at the UN.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, and then added: "If the denuclearization party was South Korea, not the United States, then there would not be such a stalemate on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula".
Moreover, Ri's tone was completely different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missile launch on US territory was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim Jong Un a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but also said there was much work to be done, and said that until North Korea was stripped of its nuclear weapons, sanctions would not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not set a time frame for it, saying: "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the enforcement of the Security Council's sanctions must continue and be continuous until we establish complete, final and verified denuclearization".
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an effort to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
