Harvard students take a course on adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year gave all students more sleep to combat the growing macho culture of caffeinated students studying all night.
Academic students at the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course by giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"A girl came up to me after I finished and said, 'Why am I only being told this now, when I'm in my final year of college?'
She said that no one had ever told her about the meaning of sleep, which surprised me", she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help them to perform well in school and athletics, and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said the decision to introduce the course came after it was found that students had suffered from severe sleep deprivation for a week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section includes a room in the dorm where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, and the importance of sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as everyone has a right to know about the health effects of smoking, Professor Scheisler added.
The culture of pride in "all-night learning" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means a growing problem of sleep deprivation.
Giving students enough quality sleep should be their secret weapon against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even prevent weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which keeps the student hungry, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he says, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving on to a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set alarms to remind them when to go to bed and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic devices and LED lights, which can disrupt circadian rhythms and lead to sleep problems.
