In 1996, a tsunami in western Donggali killed nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire, and earthquakes occur there quite regularly.
The biggest earthquakes and tsunamis in years:
2004: A major earthquake that struck the western coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: In late March and early April, a series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck the Mentawai Islands off the coast of Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck Pidie Jaya in Aceh Province, causing devastation and panic among people who still remember the devastation caused by the fatal 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
